        An NPC is much like a MONSTER.  It can do everything that a 
MONSTER can do, and more.  An npc has the ability to hold conversations,
and also allows its builders to speak through it.  An NPC is
created just like an ordinary monster, except that instead of
inheriting MONSTER, you would inherit MONSTER_RP.
 
Therefore, the first few lines of your file would look something 
like this:
 
#include <mudlib.h>
inherit MONSTER_RP;
 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
 
MONSTER_RP has a couple of functions that MONSTER does not.  These functions
have to do with telling your NPC how you want it to react to
certain stimuli.  For example, you could tell your NPC to wave
whenever someone says hi.
 
void add_response(arg1, arg2);
 
arg1 and arg2 can be strings or arrays of strings.  You can use
add_response multiple times, even with the same arguments.
  
Arg1 represents the stimuli which you want the NPC to respond to.
A caution: if the word that the NPC is looking for can be 
contained in another word, such as "hi" in "nothing", you should
make use of spacing to differentiate.  The function uses catch_tell
to search through everything the NPC sees on its screen, 
including emotes, combat spam, and even direction names.  So, you can
have the NPC respond to someone entering a room, getting an item,
or even a particular person.  
 
Arg2 contains the responses.  You can have the NPC respond in a 
variety of ways:  with a command, an emote, an echo, or a say.  If
the argument is an array, it will randomly pick an element of that
array to perform.  
 
In arg2, you can optionally precede the string with $C, $E, or $H.
If the function does not detect one of these codes, it automatically
does the entire string with a say.  NPCs automatically use
csay, and they understand all racial languages.  Including $N anywhere
in the response will cause $N to be replaced with the name of the person
it is responding to.
 
$C tells the NPC to perform the string as a command.  For example,
you could pass in "$Ckill $N" and the NPC would perform the
kill command on the person it was triggered by.  All NPCs automatically
have player commands enabled.  
 
$E causes the NPC to perform an emote, like the wizard emote, using
the string.  It automatically puts the NPC's name in front of
the string.  Therefore, if arg2 = "$Elooks out the window.", the 
NPC would emote "<monstername> looks out the window."
 
$H causes the NPC to perform an echo.  Therefore, if second 
argument was "$HYou suddenly wish you lived in Northampton.", the 
player would see "You suddenly wish you lived in Northampton."  The
function uses tell_room to accomplish this.
 
Here is a code example of the uses of add_response:
 
/*omitted NPC code*/
add_response(" hi", "Hello there!");
add_response(({"death", "died", "killed"}), "$Csob");
add_response("Greetings", ({"$Ceast", "$Esniffs quietly.", "$Eblah"}));
/*omitted NPC code*/
 
What if you want the NPC to do a series of commands?  You would
use two add_responses with the same first argument.  The add_responses
are executed in order, so the first add_response happen before the 
second add_response.
 
For example, let's say your NPC is protecting an object in the 
room, and whenever someone takes that object, it says "Don't touch
that" and attacks.  Here is how you set up the sequence.
 
add_response("gets axe", "Don't touch that!");
add_response("gets axe", "$Ckill $n");
 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
 
Another function of the NPC inheritable is builder-controlled
roleplaying.  A wizard can take control of an NPC's actions.  To
do this, one would type 'roleplay <NPCname>'.  A "wand of
control" object is cloned to your inventory.  It shows you
all that your NPC sees, and allows you to send command to the
NPC.  To send a command, you precede the command with the word
'NPC'.  As with the add_response, an NPC can do anything
a player can do, since enable_player_commands() is automatic.
While an NPC is being roleplayed all of its normal chat messages
from add_response,load_chat,load_cmd,etc will be temporarily
disabled.
 
For example, you can type 'npc east' or 'npc say hello'.  You 
will recieve feedback that you have caused the NPC to do something,
and you will see the result of what the NPC has done.  
 
Ordinarily, only the creator of a particular NPC can roleplay it.
Because some builders might want to allow other builders to roleplay 
their NPCs, there is a function to allow this.
 
To add a roleplayer to your NPC, you should include this line.
 
add_roleplayer("buildername");
 
add_roleplayer can only take a string, and it is important that the
builder's name is in all lowercase.  For each of the builders
you wish to enable, you will have to have a separate add_roleplayer line.
For example, if I wanted to allow Rampage and Souldancer to roleplay
my NPC, I would add the lines:
 
add_roleplayer("rampage");
add_roleplayer("souldancer");
 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
 
Since there is obviously so much you can do with the builder-roleplaying,
there are some guidelines as to how the NPC should and should not be
roleplayed.
 
1.) 'NPC kill' IS allowed.  It is no different to instruct
    the NPC to attack than it is to set the monster aggressive.
    Don't use an NPC to 'hunt' players you don't like, though.
 
2.) Shouting is not allowed.  It is too disruptive.
 
3.) Joining guilds, marrying, killing monsters outside your area, and
    partying are NOT allowed.  
 
4.) Helping players is not allowed.  Your NPC shouldn't help the
    players in any way.  For example, having a "guard" move out
    of the room to allow the players to pass through would be
    illegal.  Also, having your NPCs kill other monsters for
    the players' benefit would be illegal.
 
5.) As for anything else, the rules will be added as they come up.  
    Don't do anything with a NPC that you aren't allowed to
    do as a wizard.  Your NPCs can't tell a player the weapon
    class of a weapon.  Also, if you are roleplaying someone else's
    NPC, please don't do things that the creator may not want 
    you to do.
 
6.) If you use an NPC as part of a quest, actual roleplaying of that NPC should
     not be required for the quest.  Make sure any quest information  
     you provide through roleplaying is ALSO available through
     add_responses.

For your convenience, here is an example of an init function which
would tell the builder whenever a player enters the same room as said
NPC.  Init is called every time an object encounters another one.
 
 
void init () {
 ::init();
 if (!controller_ob)  //if not being roleplayed
   tell_object("persephone", "Someone is in the same room as Ananda.\n");
}
 
Of course, this could get spammy if you have a lot of npcs.
 
And that concludes the NPC documentation.
